HCP TERRAFORM OVERVIEW
HCP Terraform : collaborate , manage remote state and automate workflows
Comparing terraform with HCP Terraform :
Terraform community :   
  -  Define your infra as code
  -  Free and "code-available"
  -  Rich set of integrations (providers)
  -  Reusable modules (public registry)
  -  Ability to plan out your changes
  -  Local execution and control

HCP Terraform adds : 
  -  Managed remote state storage
  -  Consistent execution env
  -  Built-in team collaboration
  -  Role-based access control RBAC
  -  Policy enforcement Sentinal/OPA
  -  Cost estimation before apply
  -  Audit logs and compliance
  -  Private module registry

Getting connected and authenticated with HCP terraform : 

Add cloud block to HCP terraform configuration : 
terraform {
  cloud {
    organization = "my-org"
      hostname = "app.terraform.io"

    workspaces {
        project = "networking-dev"

        tags {
          name = ""
          source = "cli"
        }
    }
  
  }
}

NOTE : backend block can't exists with this cloud block at the same time.

TERRAFORM LOGIN  :
# terraform login 
  YES
token : copy paste it form the browser and paste it in the terminal.
token is saved under : /Users/username/.terraform.d/credentials.tfrc.json

API TOKEN TYPES : 

Organization tokens : manage teams, memberships and workspaces
Team tokens : Often used by automated services like CI/CD pipelines. Can run terraform operations(plan/apply)
User token : Same permission level as user account, only type of token that can access multiple orgs.
Audit tokens : provides read only access, used for accessing the audit trail API .

UNDERSTANDING TERRAFORM WORKSPACES :
CLI WORKSAPCES VS HCP TERRAFORM WORKSPACES : 
- Same configuration, multiple state files |   - complete working environments like separate state, variable, secrets,conf files ,etc
- Managed locally with terraform workspace  |  - terraform configuration + state file (with version history & rollback capacity) +
                                                variables (tf variables + env variables with sensitive marking ) + run history (full audit trail of plan/apply)
                                                 + execution settings (mode, terraform version, auto-apply ) + team access and permissions














